<br>
I was stunned over this past weekend.  It has been established that I'm officially a group snob.<br>
<br>
I was told three times in the past several days *NOT* to mez (by different people).  The tank in one group seemed to think that he could handle all two or three mobs without a problem.  Let me explain something for all you idiots that think we (enchanters) shouldn't mez.<br>
<br>
When you have multiple mobs and the tank doesn't have AoE taunt, the mobs are going to chase after the healer as soon as s/he tries to heal your sorry ass.  Not only do you run the risk of wiping the group by knocking out the healer, but even if the healer manages to live, you've now run the healer officially oom. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So we're running low on time in one particular dungeon group and the tank decides to start &quot;chain pulling&quot; mobs.  Okay, fine.  So he drags two or three back with him (remember, I've been told that I'm not supposed to mez) and as the healer starts to run lom, he says that he'll heal in between pulls.  I asked him how he was going to heal during &quot;downtime&quot; when he's supposed to be chain pulling.  He didn't respond. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Then he offers the incredible suggestion of using LoH if things get nasty with these multiple pulls.  Great, wonder boy.  What are you going to do for the next 90 minutes after you use LoH?<br>
<br>
I just don't understand what it is with some of these people that I've been grouping with.  Do anyone you know what an enchanter does?  <br>
<br>
I'm the person that can keep 4-5 mobs permanently mezzed while the cleric meds to heal your sorry ass.  I can pacify mobs so that you can pull singles.  I can save mana for the group healer by slowing.  I can increase your dps by casting haste.  I can make your mana regen faster.  I can nuke.  I can DoT.  I'm a very diverse class and can help tremendously in groups if you'll just shut up and let me do what I need to do.<br>
<br>
Also, what the deal is with shamans not slowing?  Guys, you have the *BEST* slows in the game.  I was told by one shaman that it &quot;takes too much mana.&quot;  If you're killing stuff so quickly that slow isn't really beneficial, great!  But in most of the groups I've been in, slow has been a huge benefit.  If the shaman is the main healer in a group, I have NO problem slowing.  But if you're not the main healer, learn what the strengths of your classes are.  (Note:  This isn't directed to the shaman above.  I don't think I've ever grouped with you.)<br>
<br>
Also, what the hell is it with the paladins and shadowknights not being able to keep aggro?  I'm sorry, but USE YOUR SPELLS!  I can understand a warrior having a difficult time keeping aggro unless they have weapons that proc, but I've seen paladins and shadowknights taunt mobs off a warrior anyday.  WHY CAN'T YOU GUYS DO THE SAME?!?!<br>
<br>
If I group with one more paladin or shadowknight that stops pulling because they need a &quot;med break&quot;, I think I'm going to completely lose it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
By the way, it drives me completely nuts when every single person in the group starts announcing that their buffs are fading.  I know how long my buffs last.  I have a nifty little timer that I use that tells me when your haste is about to fade.  If for some reason I forget to set it, I don't need every single one of you to tell me that you lost it at the same time.<br>
<br>
When people buff, they usually buff in group order.  When the buff fades on yourself, you refresh it and move on down the list.  When my little clarity buff icon starts blinking, I know yours is about to start blinking.  I'm already flipping through my spellbook or casting on you by the time you announce it.<br>
<br>
For heaven's sake people, learn to assist.  If you're the MT and you switch targets, CALL IT.  If mez breaks once, okay.  It was an accident.  Don't do it again.  If it breaks twice, I start to get a little annoyed.  If it breaks three or more times, I open up my spell book, replace my mez spells with my highest nuke and my gate spell.  Then I start playing wizzie. <br>
<br>
I don't usually tell people how to play their class.  But I swear, I've gotten so frustrated with some people the past few days.  I just don't understand how people can make it to their 40s or 50s without having some fundamental knowledge on how to play their class or what other classes do.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>On one note, I used to group with a wizard a long time ago who would announce &quot;nuking %t with GREAT BALL OF FIRE for 1200 dmg&quot; and I would just say, what a jerk off!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Don't spam.  Just pay attention.  Interrupt your spells (/duck) to save mana.  The only announcements I don't mind are the pulling messages, healing, mezzes, slows (usually important at higher levels so the cleric/druid/shaman knows when to begin a cheal) and evac messages.  All the other ones are useless spam.  <br>
<br>
Disclaimer:  This is only for grouping.  In raids, I want more messages so that all debuffs are done in order.  Nothing like someone dispelling slow because they didn't announce it.<br>
<br>
But anyway, I don't care how much you nuke for.  I don't care that you're backstabbing.  I don't need to hear about how you're assisting this person (everyone should know who the MT is at the start of the group - you don't need to keep reminding us).  I don't want to hear about how you're casting a DoT and how much damage it will do over how long.<br>
<br>
Just learn to do your job and I'll do mine.<br>
<br>
/rant off<br>
